Report

Welcome to the report. The report includes several sections. First, the given data was loaded and the variables were checked whether they matched with the provided documentation in 'Data Preperation' section of the report. Subsequently, the variables were explored with numerical and visual summaries and the data was cleaned out according to the obtained results. The data was modified a few times, and the reasons behind it were mentioned. In 'Data Exploration' section, the customer behaviours were examined. The data was explored to discover how the rental bikes were used during the trips. Important findings were recorded and some discoveries about the patterns of bike usage were made. In Hypothesis Testing section, the hypothesises proposed by the marketing and logistics teams were discussed and examined. Finally, a new hypothesis was introduced in 'Future Directions' part.

The visual representations of the 'distance' data reveal that there are some irrevelant values. The data includes negative values which are problematic, since the distance travelled by the customers cannot be negative. The error in this data can be attributed to the malfunction of the device whose responsibility is to measure the distance travelled with the bikes. In order to manage this error, we could either disregard the data with the negative values in 'distance' column, or replace all negative values with their positive counterpars. As a data scientist, I am suggesting to choose the second option, as neglecting this data could result in the loss of important information. The 'distance' data also includes three outliers, which could be removed to preserve the data quality and enhance data interpretation. There are no missing values observed.

As can be seen from the results, the mean distance travelled by the electric bikes is nearly 2.5 km, which is really suprising. This value means that the customers prefer the electric bikes even they have to travel very long distances, signifying their trust in our product.

                                             DATA EXPLORATION

As can be seen from the data preperation section, our company sells three types of tickets, 'single', 'season' and 'savonia'. First, the 'single' ticket type will be examined.

In [73]:
# Creating dataframe that only includes data from the 'single' ticket type
single_ticket_data = data[data['ticket'] == 'single']

# Calculating the number of trips made for the 'single' ticket type
number_of_trips = len(single_ticket_data)

# Calculating the total distance travelled for the 'single' ticket type
total_distance_travelled = single_ticket_data['distance'].sum()

# Calculating the total time travelled for the 'single' ticket type
total_time_travelled = single_ticket_data['duration'].sum()

#Calculating the total amount of fees paid for the 'single' ticket type
total_payment = single_ticket_data['cost'].sum()
# Displaying the results
print('The number of trips for the Single ticket type is {}'.format(number_of_trips))
print('The total distance travelled for the Single ticket type is {} m'.format(total_distance_travelled))
print('The total time travelled for the Single ticket type is {} s'.format(total_time_travelled))
print('The total amount of fees paid for the Single ticket type is {} euro'.format(total_payment))
print('\nThe average distance per trip for the Single ticket type is {} m'.format(total_distance_travelled/number_of_trips))
print('The average duration of the trip is {} s'.format(total_time_travelled/number_of_trips))

# Creating a new DataFrame to calculate bike surplus at each station
bike_surplus_data = pd.DataFrame()

# Determining the number of bikes arriving at each station
arrived_bikes = data['location_to'].value_counts()

# Determining the number of bikes departing from each station
departed_bikes = data['location_from'].value_counts()

# Creating a 'Station' column with station names
bike_surplus_data['Station'] = arrived_bikes.index

# Creating a 'Arrived Bikes' column with the number of arrived bikes for each station
bike_surplus_data['Arrived Bikes'] = arrived_bikes.values

# Creating a 'Departed Bikes' column with the number of departed bikes for each station
bike_surplus_data['Departed Bikes'] = departed_bikes.values

# Calculating the bike surplus at each station which will be indicated at 'Surplus' column
bike_surplus_data['Surplus'] = bike_surplus_data['Arrived Bikes'] - bike_surplus_data['Departed Bikes']

# Sorting the dataframe based on the values in 'Surplus' column
sorted_bike_surplus_data = bike_surplus_data.sort_values(by='Surplus', ascending=False)

# Dropping the old index and setting the new one
sorted_bike_surplus_data.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# Displaying the bike results
print(sorted_bike_surplus_data)

import scipy

# In order to analyze the first hypothesis proposed from the marketing team, the data should be checked whether it is normally ditributed or not
# For this purpose, the Shapiro-Wilk test will be performed. If the returned p-values are less than < 0.05, it implies that the data is not normally distributed

# Selecting the data from the 'duration' column for 'single' tickets
single_ticket_durations = data[data['ticket'] == 'single']['duration']

# Selecting the data from the 'duration' column for 'season' tickets
season_ticket_durations = data[data['ticket'] == 'season']['duration']

#Displaying the result for the data from the 'duration' column for 'single' tickets
print(scipy.stats.shapiro(single_ticket_durations))

#Displaying the result for the data from the 'duration' column for 'season' tickets
print(scipy.stats.shapiro(season_ticket_durations))

ShapiroResult(statistic=0.7511749863624573, pvalue=2.2369457294766507e-33)
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9607822299003601, pvalue=8.494552283799806e-10)

The p-values for both of the variables are less than 0.05, which means that the data is not normally distributed. Next, it should be checked whether the variables are paired or unpaired. The paired variables are dependent, while the unpaired ones are independent. The paired variables must have the same number of observations.

In [80]:
# Displaying the number of observations for the single_ticket_durations
print(len(single_ticket_durations))

# Displaying the number of observations for the season_ticket_durations
print(len(season_ticket_durations))

822
465

It is clear that the variables do not have the same number of observations, which mean that the variables are unpaired. It can be concluded that we have two unpaired and not normally distributed variables. In order to explore the statistical evidence, Mann-Whitney test will be performed for two unpaired and not normally distributed variables.

Mann-Whitney test is a nonparametric test of the null hypothesis which is the likelihood of X being greater than Y is equal to the likelihood of Y being greater than X for randomly selected values X and Y from two variables.

In [81]:
# Performing the Mann-Whitney test for the variables of single_ticket_durations and season_ticket_durations
scipy.stats.mannwhitneyu(single_ticket_durations,season_ticket_durations,\
use_continuity=True,alternative='two-sided')
Out[81]:
MannwhitneyuResult(statistic=196860.5, pvalue=0.3697537944632039)

According to our results, p-value is more than 0.05, which means that there is not enough statistical evidence to reject the null hypothesis. Thus, the results do not give us sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a significant difference between the duration of the trips made with the 'single' and 'season' tickets. In conclusion, this hypothesis is not true. Based on the results it can be said that the customers who rent the bikes with 'single' and 'season' ticket types have similar trip durations while riding the electric bikes.

Now, the second hypothesis can be evaluated.

The resultant p-value is calculated to be approximately 0.0, which means that the null hypothesis can be rejected. According to our result, there is significant statistical evidence to claim that the travel distance positively correlates with the average rate at which electricity is consumed during the trip. Based on this statement, it can be concluded that the customers who use electric bikes for longer distances are likely to utilize more energy during their trips. This insight can be taken advantage of in the promotion of our product. For example, a longer battery life can be offered to the customers who travel long distances, encouraging them to use our bikes again.
